04458nam a22007215i 9789048554324DE-B159720230228020105.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20232023ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485543247 a10.1515/97890485543242doi  a(DE-B1597)642616  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aBV660.3b.D83 2023 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a253.09022231 aDubourg, Ninon, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDisabled Clerics in the Late Middle Ages :bUn/suitable for Divine Service? /cNinon Dubourg. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (294 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPremodern Health, Disease, and Disability ;v800tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Figures -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: A Formal Dialogue -- t1 Legal Origins of the Prohibition on Clerical Disability -- t2 Aetiologies of Impairment: Congenital, Geriatric, and Acquired Conditions -- t3 Joining the Clergy -- t4 Staying in the Clergy -- t5 Leaving the Clergy -- tConclusion -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe petitions received and the letters sent by the Papal Chancery during the Late Middle Ages attest to the recognition of disability at the highest levels of the medieval Church. These documents acknowledge the existence of physical and/or mental impairments, with the papacy issuing dispensations allowing some supplicants to adapt their clerical missions according to their abilities. A disease, impairment, or old age could prevent both secular and regular clerics from fulfilling the duties of their divine office. Such conditions can, thus, be understood as forms of disability. In these cases, the Papal Chancery bore the responsibility for determining if disabled people were suitable to serve as clerics, with all the rights and duties of divine services. Whilst some petitioners were allowed to enter the clergy, or – in the case of currently serving churchmen – to stay more or less active in their work, others were compelled to resign their position and leave the clergy entirely. Petitions and papal letters lie at intersection of authorized, institutional policy and practical sources chronicling the lived experiences of disabled people in the Middle Ages. As such, they constitute an excellent analytical laboratory in which to study medieval disability in its relation to the papacy as an institution, alongside the impact of official ecclesiastical judgments on disabled lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aChurch historyyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 0aClergy with disabilities. 0aDisabilitiesxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 4aHealth and Medicine. 4aHigh Middle Ages. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aMedieval Studies. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aDisability, Clergy, Papacy, Papal Chancery, Work, Christianity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311102374840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048554324?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048554324423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048554324/original  a978-3-11-102374-8  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK